Durban - SAPS has issued a warning to all Uber and metered taxi drivers to be on high alert when driving  in KwaMashu and surrounding areas after receiving a number of complaints about robberies.  Police spokesperson,Colonel Thembeka Mbhele, said they have received reports from drivers, of criminals pretending to be clients, who want to be fetched from restaurants, night clubs or other places, to their requested destination around KwaMashu.  "The suspects stop the drivers at gunpoint and robbed them of their belongings and also their vehicles."  Mbhele said there were two incidents earlier this week.  "On Monday around 11:20 pm,  a 24-year-old driver was contacted to pick a passenger from in Phoenix destined to J section, KwaMashu. Upon arrival at a destination, a suspect ordered to be dropped and he pulled a firearm from his back and pointed it at him." She said the second suspect approached the vehicle and demanded cell phone, took cash and then he was forced to get into the boot of the car.  "In the second incident on December 31 around 10:15 pm, a 41-year-old driver was dropping a passenger in Ndlondo road in G section when the passenger paid a short fare and told the driver to wait for someone who will pay full amount ." Mbhele said all of a sudden the complainant was pointed with a fire arm. They took cash as well as his two cell phones and fled the scene. "We are appealing to the drivers to be vigilant and take extra precautions when asked to pick up clients," said Mbhele.  A case of robbery has been opened.  POST